## 5. Lemma 3: Induced one-step operator bound

For each edge, define
$$
s_{ij} = \phi_\theta(z_{ij})
$$
and the vector message
$$
m_{ij} = s_{ij}\,\hat r_{ij}.
$$

### Lemma 3

Under the assumptions of Lemma 1 and Lemma 2, there exist finite local constants $C_{\mathrm{dir}}$ and $C_{\mathrm{agg,kin}}$, depending on the rollout neighborhood, the stabilization constant, the local active neighborhood regime, and the fixed kinematic update, such that the induced one-step learned operator $\hat F$ is locally Lipschitz on $\mathcal U$ with
$$
L_{\mathrm{PHYSICK}}
\le
C_{\mathrm{agg,kin}}\, L_g \big(L_{\mathrm{bank}} + L_{\mathrm{mix}}\big) + C_{\mathrm{dir}}.
$$

### Proof

Fix two joint states $u, v \in \mathcal U$.

By Lemma 1,
$$
\|z_{ij}(u) - z_{ij}(v)\| \le L_g \|u - v\|.
$$

Applying Lemma 2 to the scalar interaction map gives
$$
|s_{ij}(u) - s_{ij}(v)|
=
|\phi_\theta(z_{ij}(u)) - \phi_\theta(z_{ij}(v))|
\le
L_g \big(L_{\mathrm{bank}} + L_{\mathrm{mix}}\big)\|u - v\|.
$$

Now decompose the message difference:
$$
m_{ij}(u) - m_{ij}(v)
=
\big(s_{ij}(u) - s_{ij}(v)\big)\hat r_{ij}(u)
+
s_{ij}(v)\big(\hat r_{ij}(u) - \hat r_{ij}(v)\big).
$$

Because $\|\hat r_{ij}(u)\| \le 1$, the first term is controlled by the scalar interaction bound above.

Because the stabilized direction map is locally Lipschitz on $\mathcal U$, and because the scalar interaction magnitude is locally bounded on $\mathcal U$, the second term is bounded by a finite local constant times $\|u - v\|$. Collect these direction-dependent contributions into $C_{\mathrm{dir}}$.

Accelerations are obtained by sum aggregation over neighbors, so the message-level bound lifts to the acceleration update with a neighborhood-dependent factor. The kinematic update is fixed and therefore Lipschitz on any bounded neighborhood. Collecting the aggregation and kinematic factors into $C_{\mathrm{agg,kin}}$ yields
$$
L_{\mathrm{PHYSICK}}
\le
C_{\mathrm{agg,kin}}\, L_g \big(L_{\mathrm{bank}} + L_{\mathrm{mix}}\big) + C_{\mathrm{dir}},
$$
which is the explicit lifted bound stated in Appendix C.1.

### Remark
This lemma is still local. It does **not** claim a graph-family-independent global constant, and it does **not** remove the dependence on the rollout neighborhood or active aggregation regime.

